In economics, the '''Backus–Smith puzzle''' or '''consumption – real-exchange-rate anomaly''' is the observation that the [[correlations]] between [[consumption (economics)|consumption]] and [[real exchange rate]]s are zero or negative.  This is contrary to economic theory which predicts that with full [[financial risk|risk]] sharing, relative consumption should be perfectly correlated with the real exchange rate. Countries with relative low prices should receive a transfer to take advantage of cheap consumption.  This anomaly was first documented by Backus and Smith (1993).<ref name="BackusSmith92">{{citation | last1 = Backus | first1 = David K.| author-link1 = David K. Backus |last2 = Smith| first2 = Gregor W.| year=1993 |title= Consumption and real exchange rates in dynamic economies with non-traded goods | journal =Journal of International Economics | volume = 35 | issue = 3–4| pages = 297–316 | doi = 10.1016/0022-1996(93)90021-O}}</ref>

